Examples of parametric curves

It is not just circles that can be represented by parametric equations, but this is perhaps the most useful parametric curve. The easiest way to actually plot a parametric curve \(x= f(t)\) and \(y = g(t)\) is to compile a table of vales as \(t\) varies, plot the points these coordinates give you, and quite literally join the dots.

Example

Sketch the curve given in parametric form by \(x= t^2\) and \(y = t^3 - 2t\).

Solution

We begin by calculating the values of \(x(t)\) and \(y(t)\) for appropriate values of \(t\). This gives us the following table:

\(t\)\(x\)\(y\)
\(-3\) \(9\) \(-21\)
\(-2\) \(4\) \(-4\)
\(-1\) \(1\) \(1\)
\(0\) \(0\) \(0\)
\(1\) \(1\) \(-1\)
\(2\) \(4\) \(4\)
\(3\) \(9\) \(21\)

As you can see, this produces a somewhat unusual curve. Expressing functions parametrically often gives us more flexibility with the graphs that we can plot.
